## ✅ API Call in `useEffect` WITHOUT AbortController

### ✅ Technique: `isMounted` flag (boolean cleanup)

***

## 🔹 Example: `Users.jsx`

```jsx
import { useEffect, useState } from "react";

export default function Users() {
  const [users, setUsers] = useState([]);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);

  useEffect(() => {
    let isMounted = true; // ✅ track component mount state

    fetch("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users")
      .then(res => res.json())
      .then(data => {
        if (isMounted) {
          setUsers(data); // ✅ update state only if mounted
          setLoading(false);
        }
      })
      .catch(error => {
        if (isMounted) {
          console.error(error);
          setLoading(false);
        }
      });

    // ✅ cleanup runs on unmount
    return () => {
      isMounted = false;
      console.log("Component unmounted, state update prevented");
    };
  }, []);

  if (loading) return <h3>Loading...</h3>;

  return (
    <ul>
      {users.map(user => (
        <li key={user.id}>{user.name}</li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
}
```

***

## 🔍 How this works (step‑by‑step)

1.  Component mounts → `isMounted = true`
2.  API request starts
3.  Component unmounts before response
4.  Cleanup runs → `isMounted = false`
5.  API resolves → `setState` is **skipped**
6.  ✅ No React warning
7.  ✅ No memory leak

