## ✅ Parent Component to Trigger Unmount

```jsx
import { useState } from "react";
import Users from "./Users";

export default function App() {
  const [show, setShow] = useState(true);

  return (
    <div>
      <button onClick={() => setShow(!show)}>
        Toggle Users
      </button>

      {show && <Users />}
    </div>
  );
}
```

Click **Toggle Users** while request is in progress → cleanup runs ✅

***

## ⚠️ Important Limitations of This Approach

❌ **API request still runs in the background**  
❌ **Network resources are not cancelled**  
✅ Only prevents `setState()` after unmount

That’s why React now recommends **AbortController** instead.

***

## ✅ Interview Comparison (Very Important)

| Approach         | Cancels API | Prevents setState | Recommended |
| ---------------- | ----------- | ----------------- | ----------- |
| `isMounted` flag | ❌ No        | ✅ Yes             | ⚠️ Legacy   |
| AbortController  | ✅ Yes       | ✅ Yes             | ✅ Best      |

***

## ✅ Interview‑Ready Answer

> Without `AbortController`, we handle API calls in `useEffect` using an `isMounted` flag.  
> The cleanup function sets the flag to `false` on unmount, and we conditionally update state only if the component is still mounted, preventing memory leaks and React warnings.

